canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111840","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111840"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 81-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of double vision and unsteadiness when walking. He has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. His regular medications include metformin, lisinopril, and aspirin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals the following when directed to look totally to his right (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://emedici.com/storage/media/QD0pPRIMEjrm9R2Il2KcwvLZr1zE3Q.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E). The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right fourth nerve palsy","Right sixth nerve palsy","Left sixth nerve palsy","Right third nerve palsy","Left third nerve palsy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and examination findings in this case are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Eright sixth nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E. The sixth cranial nerve (abducens nerve) is responsible for lateral eye movement (abduction). When damaged, it results in an inability to move the affected eye outward, causing inward deviation of the eye (esotropia) and horizontal diplopia that worsens when looking towards the affected side. In this case, the patient has been asked to look fully to his right. He is able to move the left eye fully over - but there is limited lateral movement of the right eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft sixth nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E would cause similar symptoms but in the opposite eye. The image shows that the right eye is affected, not the left, making this diagnosis incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight third nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with ptosis, a \u0027down and out\u0027 position of the eye, and pupillary involvement. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft third nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E would also present with ptosis, a \u0027down and out\u0027 position of the eye, and pupillary involvement, but in the left eye. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight fourth nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E affects the superior oblique muscle, causing vertical diplopia and difficulty with downward gaze. This doesn\u0027t match the lateral gaze deficit described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn older adults, isolated sixth nerve palsy is often due to microvascular ischemia, particularly in those with vascular risk factors such as hypertension and diabetes mellitus. However, other causes such as increased intracranial pressure, trauma, or less commonly, neoplasms should be considered. Given this patient\u0027s age and medical history, a microvascular cause is likely. However, neuroimaging (MRI or CT) would be indicated to rule out other aetiologies, especially if symptoms persist or worsen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sixth cranial nerve (abducens nerve) controls lateral eye movement.","Isolated sixth nerve palsy in older adults is often due to microvascular ischemia.","Neuroimaging is indicated in cases of sixth nerve palsy without a clear etiology or in the presence of other neurological symptoms."],"references":["Graham C, Gurnani B, Mohseni M. Abducens Nerve Palsy.. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482177/","Modi P, Arsiwalla T. Cranial Nerve III Palsy. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526112/","Azarmina M, Azarmina H. The six syndromes of the sixth cranial nerve. J Ophthalmic Vis Res. 2013 Apr;8(2):160-71. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3740468/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13870"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20812"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20812"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QD0pPRIMEjrm9R2Il2KcwvLZr1zE3Q.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/QD0pPRIMEjrm9R2Il2KcwvLZr1zE3Q.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-20T12:17:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-20T12:18:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6487"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111840"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/ap